## Scope

This slice owns the materials-management layer and the units spine: a boundary unit-of-measure vocabulary with net-new eV/cm⁻¹ conversions, a data-driven dispersion-model coefficient catalogue, a searchable categorised materials library, refractiveindex.info/CSV import-export, dispersion-preview plot routing with a spectral-unit toggle, and optional thermo-optic dn/dT parameters. It fills the units-spine architecture that slice 001 (Part A §A.10) fixed but did not author, so it lands before Part B/E which consume `UnitOfMeasure` and the conversion seam. No engine code is forked; no domain payload stores a non-SI unit.

## Requirements

The following are the parent's Part D directives, reproduced verbatim. Contractful identifiers and `<file>:<line>` references are preserved exactly.

### R-1 (D.1) Define the boundary unit-of-measure vocabulary as a net-new DU [Core]

This part MUST add a new module `Units.fs` in `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` defining a discriminated union `UnitOfMeasure` enumerating exactly the human-facing units 010 §2 names: `Meter | Millimeter | Micrometer | Nanometer | Angstrom | ElectronVolt | Wavenumber`. This DU is the ONLY place a non-SI unit name appears in the solution; it is a UI/IO label, never a storage type. The module MUST NOT introduce new F# `[<Measure>]` types for Å, eV, or cm⁻¹ that shadow `Constants.fs` — length units reduce through the existing measures `nm`/`mkm`/`mm`/`meter` (`Constants.fs:6,10,13,17`); Å, eV and cm⁻¹ are handled by the scalar conversions in D.2. The DU MUST be the F# realisation of the `unitOfMeasure` `$def` Part A reserves in `optical-constructor-project.schema.json` (§A.7); this part fills that `$def` as a string `enum` of the seven member names and MUST NOT add members absent from 010 §2.

### R-2 (D.2) Implement boundary length-and-energy conversions reusing engine constants [Core]

`Units.fs` MUST provide two total functions, `toMeters : UnitOfMeasure -> float -> float<meter>` and `toWaveLength : UnitOfMeasure -> float -> WaveLength`, that convert a human-entered scalar into the engine's canonical base. For `Meter`/`Millimeter`/`Micrometer`/`Nanometer` the implementation MUST multiply by the existing constants `mmToMeter`/`mkmToMeter`/`nmToMeter` (`Constants.fs:27,30,33`) and MUST NOT re-derive those factors. For `Angstrom` the factor MUST be `1.0e-10<meter>` per Å. For `ElectronVolt` the function MUST first map energy to wavelength by `λ[nm] = 1239.84 / E[eV]` then through `nmToMeter`; for `Wavenumber` it MUST map `λ[nm] = 1.0e7 / ν̃[cm⁻¹]` then through `nmToMeter`. The literal `1239.84` MUST appear exactly once, as a named binding `let evNmProduct = 1239.84` carrying a doc-comment citing `E[eV] = 1239.84 / λ[nm]`. The inverse functions `fromMeters : UnitOfMeasure -> float<meter> -> float` and `wavelengthToUnit : UnitOfMeasure -> WaveLength -> float` MUST be provided for display, dividing by the same constants and inverting the eV/cm⁻¹ relations; `wavelengthToUnit` MUST read the canonical value via `WaveLength.value` (`Fields.fs:284`). These functions are the SOLE conversion seam — no other module in the solution MAY hand-roll a unit conversion.

### R-3 (D.3) Reuse `WaveLength` at the engine boundary; do not fork it [Core]

When a converted value re-enters the engine it MUST be carried as the engine's `WaveLength` DU (`Fields.fs:280`), constructed via its `Nm`/`Mkm` cases or `WaveLength.nm`/`WaveLength.mkm` (`Fields.fs:294,295`). `toWaveLength Nanometer` and `toWaveLength Micrometer` MUST return `Nm`/`Mkm` respectively so the engine's own `.value` reduction (`Fields.fs:286,287`) performs the final SI step; for `Angstrom`, `ElectronVolt` and `Wavenumber` — which `WaveLength` cannot represent natively — `toWaveLength` MUST first reduce to nm (D.2) and return `Nm`. This part MUST NOT add `Angstrom`/`Ev`/`Wavenumber` cases to the engine's `WaveLength` DU; the boundary DU `UnitOfMeasure` (D.1) is the place those live, and the engine continues to see only `Mkm`/`Nm`.

### R-4 (D.4) Attach a per-element default unit to project elements via Part A's aggregate [Core]

This part MUST define a record `defaultUnit : UnitOfMeasure` field carried on each unit-bearing project element (layer/element/source) inside the `OpticalConstructorProject` aggregate Part A owns (§A.7). This part does NOT redefine that aggregate; it specifies that the per-element default-unit value uses the D.1 DU and is the value rendered/edited in the UI and persisted in JSON. The default-unit value is metadata about *display only*: it MUST NOT influence the stored canonical SI value, and round-tripping a project through JSON MUST preserve both the canonical SI datum and its `defaultUnit` label independently. The schema `$def` `unitOfMeasure` (§A.7) is the JSON shape; the per-element placement (which records carry a `defaultUnit`) is fixed by Part B (stack/layer) and Part E (sources) and MUST NOT be re-specified here beyond the requirement that the carried type is `UnitOfMeasure`.

### R-5 (D.5) Define the dispersion-model coefficient catalogue as data, not code [Core]

This part MUST add a module `DispersionModels.fs` in `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` defining one F# record per analytic model named in 010 §2 — `Sellmeier`, `Cauchy`, `Lorentz` (Drude–Lorentz), `Drude`, `TaucLorentz`, `GaussianOscillator`, and `ConstantNK` (constant n+ik) — each holding ONLY its coefficient scalars (e.g. Sellmeier `b` and `c` term lists; Cauchy `a`,`b`,`c`; Drude plasma/damping frequencies; constant `n`,`k`). A wrapping DU `DispersionModel` MUST enumerate these records so the editor and schema can describe a single tagged choice. Each record MUST carry an explicit `wavelengthUnit : UnitOfMeasure` (D.1) naming the unit its coefficients were tabulated in (Sellmeier `c` terms are conventionally µm²), so evaluation (D.6) can normalise to the engine's meter base. This catalogue MUST be the realisation of the schema `$def` `materialEntry` dispersion sub-object (§A.7); coefficient field shapes are owned here. Schema versioning of these coefficient records is OUT OF SCOPE.

### R-6 (D.6) Evaluate each model to an `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` reusing the engine's closure shape [Core]

`DispersionModels.fs` MUST provide `evaluate : DispersionModel -> (WaveLength -> ComplexRefractionIndex)`, returning a closure of exactly the shape `Silicon`/`Langasite` build by hand (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:87,52`). The closure MUST read the canonical wavelength via `WaveLength.value` (`Fields.fs:284`), normalise it against the record's `wavelengthUnit` (D.5) using D.2, apply the analytic formula, and return a `ComplexRefractionIndex` (`MaterialProperties.fs:43`). A second function `toOpticalProperties : DispersionModel -> OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` MUST compose that closure into an `EpsWithDisp` via `Eps.fromComplexRefractionIndex` (`MaterialProperties.fs:87`) wrapped as `EpsWithDisp` (the `EpsWithDisp` case of the `EpsWithDisp` DU, `Dispersion.fs:9-10`), with `muWithDisp = Mu.vacuum.dispersive` and `rhoWithDisp = Rho.vacuum.dispersive` for isotropic entries — mirroring `Silicon`'s record (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:90-95`). This part MUST NOT re-derive the matrix-exponential or EVD math seams and MUST NOT add a parallel tensor type; it reuses `OpticalProperties` (`MaterialProperties.fs:165`) end to end. The constant-n+ik model MUST emit `EpsWithoutDisp` (`Dispersion.fs:11`) so a non-dispersive entry incurs no closure overhead.

### R-7 (D.7) Support anisotropic entries through the existing three-index constructor [Standard]

For uniaxial (n_o, n_e) and biaxial (n_x, n_y, n_z) material definitions, `DispersionModels.fs` MUST build the principal-axis tensor by calling the engine's existing three-argument `Eps.fromComplexRefractionIndex (n1, n2, n3)` (`MaterialProperties.fs:87`), mapping uniaxial as `(n_o, n_e, n_o)`. Each principal index MAY itself be a per-axis `DispersionModel` (D.5) so an anisotropic crystal can disperse differently along each axis, exactly as `Langasite` evaluates ordinary and extraordinary indices separately (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:52-55`). Crystal-axis orientation MUST NOT be implemented here: rotation reuses `Layer.rotate` (`Media.fs:30`) and is owned by the stack editor (Part B). Full hand-entered ε/µ/ρ tensors and gyration reuse `Eps.create`/`Mu.create`/`Rho.create` (`MaterialProperties.fs:62,112,138`) and MUST NOT be re-typed in this part.

### R-8 (D.8) Define the searchable, categorised materials library aggregate [Core]

This part MUST add a module `MaterialLibrary.fs` in `OpticalConstructor.Domain.fsproj` defining `MaterialEntry` — a record holding a display name, a category DU `MaterialCategory = Glass | Metal | Semiconductor | Crystal`, an optional `description : string` (reusing the description convention §A.7, mirroring the engine's `description` fields e.g. `OpticalSystemWithDisp.description`, `Dispersion.fs:141`), and its `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` (`Dispersion.fs:53`) produced by D.6/D.7 — and a `MaterialLibrary` record holding the entry list plus pure search/filter functions `byCategory` and `byNameContains`. Built-in entries MUST include the already-coded `siliconOpticalProperties` and `langasiteOpticalProperties` (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:98,99`) and the `Standard` glass/crystal presets (`OpticalProperties/Standard.fs:64-70`) wrapped as `MaterialEntry` values; this part MUST NOT re-derive their dispersion. The library is in-memory and additive; persistence of the library is the JSON `materialEntry` `$def` (§A.7) handled by Part A's storage seam, and a separate shareable library file format is owned by Part I (§I.8). Search indexing/caching is OUT OF SCOPE — filtering is a linear `List.filter`.

### R-9 (D.9) Import from refractiveindex.info YAML and CSV; export CSV [Core]

This part MUST add a module `MaterialImport.fs` in `OpticalConstructor.Storage.fsproj` providing `importRefractiveIndexInfo : string -> Result<MaterialEntry, ImportError>` and `importCsv : string -> Result<MaterialEntry, ImportError>`, parsing the open refractiveindex.info YAML layout (tabulated `n`/`k` vs λ, and the `formula 1..` Sellmeier/Cauchy coefficient blocks) and tab/comma data via FSharp.Data (the import library named in §A.7). Every parsed wavelength column MUST be reduced to the engine base by D.2 according to the file's declared unit (refractiveindex.info tabulates λ in µm), producing either a tabulated `WaveLength -> ComplexRefractionIndex` closure or a `DispersionModel` (D.5) that feeds D.6. Tabulated entries MUST interpolate between sampled points so the resulting closure is total over the chart range; interpolation is linear in λ and MUST NOT introduce a caching layer. Export MUST provide `exportCsv : MaterialEntry -> Range<WaveLength> -> string` sampling n,k over the range using the entry's `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp.getEps` (`Dispersion.fs:13`). YAML export, retries, and schema-versioned import are OUT OF SCOPE; `Result<_, ImportError>` is the error channel (errors as values, not exceptions). The canonical project still serialises as JSON (§A.7) — these importers produce in-memory `MaterialEntry` values and MUST NOT pickle them with FsPickler.

### R-10 (D.10) Route library entries into the existing dispersion-preview plots with a spectral-unit toggle [Standard]

The material-preview surface in `OpticalConstructor.Ui.fsproj` MUST plot n(λ)/k(λ) (and ρ, ε components) by calling the engine's existing `plotN11`/`plotXi11`/`plotN22`/`plotXi22`/`plotN33`/`plotXi33`/`plotRho11` functions (`Analytics/Charting.fs:95-107`), passing the selected `MaterialEntry`'s `OpticalPropertiesWithDisp` (D.8) and a `Range<WaveLength>` (`Variables.fs:22`) built from the user's range. This part MUST NOT re-implement dispersion plotting. The spectral axis MUST expose a unit toggle covering nm / µm / Å / eV / cm⁻¹ implemented by D.2's `wavelengthToUnit` at the chart boundary ONLY; the underlying `Range<WaveLength>` and the engine data stay in canonical meters (the toggle relabels/rescales the axis, it does not re-store data). Building the `Range<WaveLength>` from user-entered endpoints MUST use D.2 `toWaveLength` so an EUV user can request the range in eV and a green-laser user in nm without manual conversion.

### R-11 (D.11) Forbid non-SI storage and duplicate-conversion paths [Core]

No module added by this part MAY store a value in a non-SI unit in any domain record, JSON payload, or `.binz` sidecar (§0 constraint 3). The `defaultUnit`/`wavelengthUnit` labels (D.4, D.5) are the ONLY persisted unit names and they label *display intent*, never the datum. All unit arithmetic MUST go through `Units.fs` (D.2); any other module needing a conversion MUST call those functions rather than multiplying by a literal factor. This part MUST NOT add backwards-compatibility shims for pre-existing material files, MUST NOT add a config knob to change the canonical base, and MUST NOT introduce a second wavelength type alongside the engine's `WaveLength` (`Fields.fs:280`).

### R-12 (D.12) Temperature/composition dependence (thermo-optic dn/dT) as optional model parameters [Standard]

`DispersionModels.fs` MUST support the [Standard] temperature/composition dependence of 010 §2 (thermo-optic dn/dT, 010 lines 164-165) as OPTIONAL parameters on a `DispersionModel`, never as a mandatory field. This part MUST add a net-new record `ThermoOptic = { dndT : float<1/K>; referenceTemperature : float<K> }` in `DispersionModels.fs` and an OPTIONAL `thermoOptic : ThermoOptic option` carried alongside the model's coefficient record; when `None`, evaluation (D.6) MUST be byte-for-byte the isothermal result with no closure overhead (mirroring the `EpsWithoutDisp` no-overhead rule of D.6). When `Some`, the `evaluate` closure (D.6) MUST apply a first-order thermo-optic correction `n(λ, T) = n(λ, referenceTemperature) + dndT · (T − referenceTemperature)` at the chosen operating temperature `T : float<K>`, returning a `ComplexRefractionIndex` (`MaterialProperties.fs:43`); the correction MUST compose with the existing closure shape (`OpticalProperties/Dispersive.fs:87`) and MUST NOT introduce a parallel tensor type. Temperature MUST be stored in kelvin (the engine has no kelvin measure today; `[<Measure>] K` is net-new and lives in `DispersionModels.fs`, not a shadow of `Constants.fs`), and `dndT` MUST be stored in canonical per-kelvin units — neither value is a length/energy, so the §0 canonical-units rule is satisfied by storing SI K and 1/K, and NO non-SI unit is admitted. The operating temperature `T` MUST be supplied by the caller at the evaluation boundary and MUST NOT be persisted into the per-material coefficient record; only `dndT`/`referenceTemperature` persist, as the `materialEntry` dispersion sub-object's optional thermo-optic fields (the `materialEntry` `$def`, §A.7). This part MUST NOT add full temperature-dependent Sellmeier tables, composition-interpolation tables, or a thermal-expansion model — only the first-order dn/dT optional parameter named in 010 §2.

## Non-requirements

- The `OpticalConstructorProject` aggregate itself is NOT redefined here (owned by Part A / slice 001); this slice only adds the `defaultUnit : UnitOfMeasure` field requirement (D.4) and the dispersion sub-object shapes. Per-element placement is fixed by Part B (slice 003) and Part E (slice 005).
- Crystal-axis orientation / rotation is NOT implemented here — it reuses `Layer.rotate` and is owned by Part B (slice 003).
- The shareable material-library file format and the JSON `materialEntry` persistence wiring are owned by Part I (slice 009); this slice produces in-memory `MaterialEntry` values only.
- Caching of evaluated dispersion curves, model-coefficient schema versioning, retry/back-off on import, migration of legacy material files (§0 constraint 6).

